I will start by rewriting 6 and 36 as $6^1$ and $6^2$:
\begin{aligned} (6^1)^{12}\div (6^2)^5 \end {aligned}
Now I can use this property of exponents: when you raise a power to a power, you multiply to exponents.
\begin{aligned}  6^{1\cdot12}\div 6^{2\cdot5} \end {aligned}
\begin{aligned} 6^{12}\div 6^{10}  \end {aligned}
I also can use this rule of exponents:
\begin{aligned}  \frac{x^n}{x^m}=x^{n-m} \end {aligned}
So this equals:
\begin{aligned} 6^{12-10} \end {aligned}
Now let's subtract:
\begin{aligned} 12-10=2 \end {aligned}
So the expression simplifies to:
\begin{aligned} 6^2 \end {aligned}
